media.altText: every month with chronic & mental illness in the US is like please ma'am may I have some more of the medications that make me not die I've been a very good boy. and the doctor is like of course. let me ask the corporations. and then I call the pharmacy a few days later like hey so my doctor said I'm allowed to live. can I have those medications...the corporations said I couldn't ask for them any earlier so I'm out now...and they're like oh, some inexplicable delay has occurred with the corporations or the mail or our computer, even though you do this here every single month and have for years now. and then a week and a few calls later the corporation is like "ugh.....fine. you may live. that'll be hundreds of dollars." and I'm like "why am I even asking you if you're not going to pay for this" and they're like there is simply no other way this can happen without me making billions of dollars and as I'm sure you understand that is the greater good. see you next month if you live!

rawContent:
I feel like the biggest misconception about #depression is that it’s an overwhelming sadness.

That’s only a part of it.

Another part is what I like to describe as an overwhelming nothing.

There’s no sadness or melancholy… Just nothing.

That nothing is extremely distressing…

01.Child's Pose (Balasana):
02.Bridge Pose (Setu Bandhasana):
03.Standing Forward Fold (Uttanasana):
04.Warrior II (Virabhadrasana II):
05.Legs-Up-The-Wall Pose (Viparita Karani):

Remember, yoga is not a substitute for professional help or treatment for depression. If you are experiencing symptoms of depression, it is important to seek guidance from a healthcare professional. Yoga can be a complementary practice to support your overall well-being and mental health journey.
